title: Impostor syndrome
description: Doubting accomplishments, fear of being exposed as a fraud.

title: Event Sourcing
description: Pattern of using events as the source of truth for data storage.

title: Golang
description: Programming language. Go has a very powerful standard library, making it easy to write code without an excessive number of dependencies. It also has built-in support for open-source dependencies, so it doesn't require an external package manager.

title: TypeScript
description: TypeScript is a strongly-typed variant of JavaScript. It adds additional safety and scalability at the cost of ease of project startup time.

title: The Minto Pyramid Principle
description: A way to organize information to be maximally understandable. One of the more compelling pieces of this to me is to always start with somnething that you agree on.

title: React
description: An unopinionated JavaScript framework. The primary features are a) declarativeness and b) HTML-like syntax called JSX.

links.description: React is a framework written in JavaScript.

title: Stanford duck syndrome
description: When a person puts effort into appearing effortless, when under the surface they are struggling.

links.description: Duck syndrome can contribute to impostor syndrome. When it appears that everyone else's work is effortless, the fact that one's own work is not is disturbing.

title: Monkey on the back
description: When a manager doesn't give a subordinate the tools to meaningfully address a problem to the manager's satisfaction.

title: Atomic Design
description: A way of creating design systems that emphasizes composability and reusability.

title: Code linting
description: A tool to analyze source code to find errors as well as stylistic problems.

title: Consciouesness/competence model
description:
There are four stages to knowledge acquisition:

1. **Unconscious incompetence**: You don't know what you don't know.

1. **Conscious incompetence**: You know what you don't know.

1. **Conscious competence**: You know, but you have to think about it.

1. **Unconscious competence**: You know, and you don't have to think about it.

![](https://miro.medium.com/max/674/1*wQz9hug8PWf2ke0eqE3-yg.jpeg)

title: Technical debt
description: Features of code which make it difficult to maintain or extend. While frequently taken on to hit deadlines, technical debt can also be the result of poor foresight.

title: Code refactoring
description: When a developer rewrites code to be more extensible, legible, or maintainable.

links.description: Code refactoring can be a way to combat technical debt, but when taken overboard can also contribute to it due to over-abstraction.

title: "I" statements
description: Feedback statements in the form **I feel _blank_ when you _blank_. Please _blank_.** They help the feedback receiver focus attention on the feedback giver rather than their own faults.
